"Latif Mojib M., Keenlyside N.S.","A perspective on decadal climate variability and predictability",2011,"Deep-Sea Research Part II: Topical Studies in Oceanography","58","17-18",,"1880","1894",,,10.1016/j.dsr2.2010.10.066,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79960328532&partnerID=40&md5=069bbd19cab5969a9e529964f305ebd1","Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften an der Universität Kiel, Düsternbrooker Weg 20, 24105 Kiel, Germany","Latif Mojib, M., Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften an der Universität Kiel, Düsternbrooker Weg 20, 24105 Kiel, Germany; Keenlyside, N.S., Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften an der Universität Kiel, Düsternbrooker Weg 20, 24105 Kiel, Germany","The global surface air temperature record of the last 150 years is characterized by a long-term warming trend, with strong multidecadal variability superimposed. Similar multidecadal variability is also seen in other (societal important) parameters such as Sahel rainfall or Atlantic hurricane activity. The existence of the multidecadal variability makes climate change detection a challenge, since global warming evolves on a similar timescale. The ongoing discussion about a potential anthropogenic signal in the Atlantic hurricane activity is an example. A lot of work was devoted during the last years to understand the dynamics of the multidecadal variability, and external and internal mechanisms were proposed. This review paper focuses on two aspects. First, it describes the mechanisms for internal variability using a stochastic framework. Specific attention is given to variability of the Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation (AMOC), which is likely the origin of a considerable part of decadal variability and predictability in the Atlantic Sector. Second, the paper discusses decadal predictability and the factors limiting its realization. These include a poor understanding of the mechanisms involved and large biases in state-of-the-art climate models. Enhanced model resolution, improved subgrid scale parameterisations, and the inclusion of additional climate subsystems, such as a resolved stratosphere, may help overcome these limitations. © 2011 Elsevier Ltd.","Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation; Atlantic Multidecadal Variability; Climate modelling; Climate prediction; Decadal climate variability; Systematic model error","Atlantic meridional overturning circulations; Climate modelling; Climate prediction; Decadal climate variability; Multidecadal variability; Systematic models; Atmospheric temperature; Climatology; Global warming; Hurricanes; Climate models; air temperature; climate change; climate modeling; climate prediction; decadal variation; error analysis; human activity; hurricane; literature review; marine atmosphere; meridional circulation; numerical model; overturn; parameterization; rainfall; stratosphere; thermohaline circulation; timescale; warming; Atlantic Sector; Southern Ocean",,,,,,"Alvarez-Garcia, F., Latif, M., Biastoch, A., On multidecadal and quasi-decadal North Atlantic variability (2008) J. Climate, 21, pp. 3433-3452; Bader, J., Latif, M., North Atlantic Oscillation response to anomalous Indian Ocean SST in a coupled GCM (2005) J. Climate, 18, pp. 5382-5389; Barsugli, J.J., Battisti, D.S., The basic effects of atmosphere-ocean thermal coupling on midlatitude variability (1998) J. Atmos. Sci., 55, pp. 477-493; Bengtsson, L., How may tropical cyclones change in a warmer climate? (2007) Tellus, 59 A, pp. 539-561; Biastoch, A., Böning, C., Lutjeharms, J., Agulhas leakage dynamics affects decadal variability in Atlantic Overturning Circulation (2008) Nature, p. 456; Biasutti, M., Giannini, A., Robust Sahel drying in response to late 20th century forcings (2006) Geophys. Res. Lett., 33, pp. L11706; Bjerknes, J., Atlantic air-sea interaction (1964) Advances in Geophysics, Academic Press, 10, pp. 1-82; Böning, C.W., Dispert, A., Visbeck, M., Rintoul, S.R., Schwarzkopf, F.U., The response of the Antarct